{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.02,0.19,0.1,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81680"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"884"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8840"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81680"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-hour history of left eye pain following accidental trauma with a pencil. He reports pain, irritation and foreign body sensation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His left eye shows no corneal infiltrate. Visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes. Fluorescein staining reveals an epithelial defect on the cornea (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features would warrant immediate ophthalmology referral?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased fluorescein uptake at the site of injury","Initial difficulty opening the eye","Location of abrasion over the pupil","Marked photophobia","Reduction in visual acuity"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a corneal abrasion, which is a defect in the corneal epithelium typically caused by mechanical trauma. Most corneal abrasions heal well within 48 hours with appropriate primary care management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduction in visual acuity\u003C/strong\u003E is a red flag that requires immediate ophthalmology assessment as it may indicate more serious injury to deeper corneal layers or other ocular structures. Normal visual acuity, as seen in this case, is reassuring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased fluorescein uptake at the site of injury\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic finding that confirms the diagnosis of corneal abrasion. This is an expected finding and does not itself warrant specialist referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial difficulty opening the eye\u003C/strong\u003E is common due to pain and photophobia (light sensitivity). This protective response is typical and improves with topical anaesthetic drops during examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocation of abrasion over the pupil\u003C/strong\u003E is not itself an indication for referral if visual acuity remains normal and there are no other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarked photophobia\u003C/strong\u003E is an expected symptom of corneal abrasion due to ciliary muscle spasm and does not require specialist referral unless accompanied by other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary care management typically includes topical antibiotic prophylaxis and follow-up within 24 hours to ensure healing. Other indications for ophthalmology referral include worsening symptoms, failure to improve within 48 hours, or development of corneal infiltrate suggesting infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Corneal abrasions typically present with pain, photophobia, and foreign body sensation but usually heal well within 48 hours.","Reduced visual acuity in corneal abrasion requires urgent ophthalmology assessment.","Simple corneal abrasions can be managed in primary care with topical antibiotics and 24-hour follow-up."],"references":["Eye emergency manual: an illustrated guide. NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. 2023. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf","Wipperman. J, Dorsch. J. Evaluation and Management of Corneal Abrasions, Am Fam Physician. 2013 Jan 15;87(2):114-120.","Arbabi EM, Kelly RJ, Carrim ZI. Corneal ulcers in general practice. Br J General Practice 2018; 68: 49\u201350."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17574"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17574"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/db227256-6b1b-434e-a5c1-64f9f53f340c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.